\lt{S}{3\,\colvector{1\\2\\3}}&=\lt{S}{\colvector{3\\6\\9}}=\colvector{24\\0\\28}

proof.p:
The two zero vectors in the conclusion of the theorem are different.  The first is from $U$ while the second is from $V$.  We will subscript the zero vectors in this proof to highlight the distinction.  Think about your objects.  (This proof is contributed by ).

\lt{T}{\zerovector_U}
&=\lt{T}{0\zerovector_U}
&&\text{ in }U\\
&=0\lt{T}{\zerovector_U}
&&\\
&=\zerovector_V
&&\text{ in }V

