1&1&3&-7
\end{bmatrix}

and define a function $\ltdefn{P}{\complex{4}}{\complex{3}}$ by

\lt{P}{\vect{x}}=A\vect{x}

So we are using an old friend, the matrix-vector product () as a way to convert a vector with 4 components into a vector with 3 components.  Applying  allows us to write the defining formula for $P$ in a slightly different form,

\lt{P}{\vect{x}}=A\vect{x}=
\begin{bmatrix}
3&-1&8&1\\
2&0&5&-2\\
1&1&3&-7
\end{bmatrix}
\colvector{x_1\\x_2\\x_3\\x_4}
=
x_1\colvector{3\\2\\1}+
x_2\colvector{-1\\0\\1}+
x_3\colvector{8\\5\\3}+
x_4\colvector{1\\-2\\-7}

Almost forgot  we should verify that $P$ is indeed a linear transformation.  This is easy with two matrix properties from .

\lt{P}{\vect{x}+\vect{y}}
&=A\left(\vect{x}+\vect{y}\right)&&\text{Definition of $P$}\\
&=A\vect{x}+A\vect{y}&&\\
&=\lt{P}{\vect{x}}+\lt{P}{\vect{y}}&&\text{Definition of $P$}
and
\lt{P}{\alpha\vect{x}}
&=A\left(\alpha\vect{x}\right)&&\text{Definition of $P$}\\
&=\alpha\left(A\vect{x}\right)&&\\
&=\alpha\lt{P}{\vect{x}}&&\text{Definition of $P$}

Define the function $\ltdefn{R}{\complex{3}}{\complex{4}}$ by

\lt{R}{\colvector{x_1\\x_2\\x_3}}=
